        <h1>2. <%= @page_title_2 %></h1>
      </header>

      <div id="govspeak">
        <p>You can usually take part of your pension pot as a tax-free lump sum. Most pension schemes offer this.</p>

        <p>There are 2 ways you can take your tax-free lump sum.</p>

        <h2 id="take-your-lump-sum-in-one-go">Take your lump sum in one go</h2>
        <p>You can take 25% of your whole pension pot tax-free. After that you have to pay Income Tax on any payments, eg from an <span class="tooltip" title="Gives you a regular income in your retirement">annuity</span> or when you take more cash from your pot.</p>

        <p>For example, your pot is £60,000 and you take £15,000 tax-free in one go. Any payments you get from the remaining £45,0000 would be taxed.</p>

        <h2 id="take-smaller-sums">Take smaller sums</h2>
        <p>You can take smaller cash sums from your pension pot -  25% of each sum will be tax-free.</p>

        <p>For example, your pot is £60,000 and you take £1,000 out as cash every month. £250 of this amount would be tax-free every time. The remaining £750 would be taxed.</p>

        <div class="application-notice info-notice">
          <p>Use the <a href="/pension-tax-calculator">Pension tax calculator</a> to find out how much you get after tax if you cash in your whole pot.</p>
        </div>

